title: Instant Analysis | FSU rolls by U of L
text:
Instant Analysis | FSU rolls by U of L Steve Jones , @stevejones_cj 7:55 p.m. EDT October 17, 2015 VIDEOS | U OF L-FLORIDA STATE POSTGAME Video | Bobby Petrino FSU postgame interview | 07:00 Louisville coach discusses 41-21 loss. 1 of 4 VIDEOS | U OF L-FLORIDA STATE POSTGAME Video | QB Lamar Jackson discusses FSU loss | 03:52 Jackson: "We've just got to keep pushing ourselves." 2 of 4 VIDEOS | U OF L-FLORIDA STATE POSTGAME Video | Jaylen Smith FSU postgame | 04:05 Louisville WR had five catches for 38 yards. 3 of 4 VIDEOS | U OF L-FLORIDA STATE POSTGAME Video | OLB Trevon Young's post-FSU remarks | 03:22 Senior had two sacks in 41-21 loss. 4 of 4 Video | Bobby Petrino FSU postgame interview Video | QB Lamar Jackson discusses FSU loss Video | Jaylen Smith FSU postgame Video | OLB Trevon Young's post-FSU remarks Oct 17, 2015; Tallahassee, FL, USA; Louisville player James Quick (17) makes a reception against the Florida State Seminoles at Doak Campbell Stadium. Mandatory Credit: Glenn Beil-USA TODAY Sports (Photo: Glenn Beil, Glenn Beil-USA TODAY Sports) 5 CONNECT 9 TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
TALLAHASSEE, Fla. - Some high and low points from Louisville’s 41-21 loss at Florida State in which the No. 11 Seminoles improved to 6-0 (4-0 ACC) and the Cardinals fell to 2-4 (1-2). 
Offensive Player of the Game: Receiver James Quick hauled in five catches for 130 yards and all three of Louisville’s touchdowns – of 18, 19 and 39 yards. In the first quarter, Lamar Jackson had two consecutive wide-open completions to Quick down the middle of the field, for 48 and 18 yards, for the first score. It was Louisville’s first three-TD receiving game since DeVante Parker against Kentucky last year. 
Defensive Player of the Game: Rush end Trevon Young recorded his first two sacks of the season, including a fast, violent takedown of Florida State quarterback Everett Golson on a third down in the second quarter. Young also had a QB hurry. 
Where the Game Turned: Louisville had a third-quarter meltdown. U of L lost a 7-6 lead early in the period on Dalvin Cook’s tackle-shedding 54-yard run, but the Cards responded quickly with Jackson’s 19-yard touchdown pass to Quick. After that, FSU struck back with another big scoring play. Golson connected over the middle to receiver Kermit Whitfield, who sprinted down the right sideline for 70 yards with 8:05 left in the third. That put FSU ahead 20-14. On U of L’s ensuing drive, Jackson was blasted and fumbled the ball away on a sack by Derwin James. That set up another FSU TD drive that included a targeting flag – an ejection – on Louisville linebacker Keith Brown. Jackson was picked off on the first play of Louisville’s next drive. It was suddenly 27-14 Florida State, and the Noles added a TD early in the fourth. 
Key Stat: FSU extended its winning streak against ACC competition to 28 games and its home winning streak to 18 games. Louisville hasn't won in Tallahassee since 1952. 
What Went Right: Jackson, who’d done most of his damage this season running the ball, was effective throwing the ball against Florida State, aside from the interception. He completed 20 of 35 passes for career highs of 307 yards and three TDs. He ran 19 times for 32 yards, including losing the fumble. 
What Went Wrong: Cook, an early candidate for the Heisman Trophy, gave FSU its first lead at the 13:09 mark of the third quarter on the 54-yard touchdown run in which he broke four Louisville tackles. Cook recorded 135 of his 163 rushing yards in the second half as Florida State bounced back from having zero rushing yards as a team at halftime. Golson added 372 passing yards.
